    <h1 class="article-title">How Air Pollution Creates Acid Rain</h1>
    <p class="article-desc">Discover the fascinating chemistry behind one of the world's most damaging environmental problems - and learn why your car exhaust contributes to dissolving ancient monuments.</p>
    <div class="meta">8 min read · Includes video · 3 research links</div>
  </div>

  <div class="video-wrapper">
    <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/1nOhIgWCHOE" title="Acid Rain Chemistry Explained" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>
  </div>

  <div class="section-label">The reaction</div>
  <div class="equation-box">
    <span class="eq-part" style="color:#AFA9EC;">SO₂ + H₂O + ½O₂</span>
    <span class="eq-arrow">→</span>
    <span class="eq-part" style="color:#9FE1CB;">H₂SO₄</span>
  </div>

  <p class="body-text">Every time you see rain falling from the sky, you're witnessing a natural process that's been altered by human activity. What should be pure water (with a neutral pH of around 7) has become slightly acidic due to chemical reactions happening high in our atmosphere. Even "normal" rainwater is actually mildly acidic with a pH around 5.6, but acid rain can have a pH as low as 4.3 - that's nearly as acidic as orange juice!</p>
  <p class="body-text">The culprits behind acid rain are sulfur dioxide (SO₂) and nitrogen oxides (NOₓ) released from burning fossil fuels in power plants, factories, and vehicles. When these compounds rise into the atmosphere, they undergo fascinating chemical transformations that turn them into strong acids. The sulfur dioxide reaction shown above is just one part of this complex atmospheric chemistry.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-title">pH Scale Connection</div>
    <div class="callout-text">Remember that the pH scale is logarithmic - each unit represents a 10-fold change in acidity. So acid rain with pH 4.3 is actually 10 times more acidic than normal rain at pH 5.3, and 100 times more acidic than pure water at pH 7!</div>
  </div>

  <p class="body-text">The formation process involves multiple steps. First, sulfur dioxide from coal-burning power plants combines with water vapor and oxygen in the atmosphere to form sulfuric acid (H₂SO₄). Similarly, nitrogen oxides from car exhausts react with water to form nitric acid (HNO₃). These acids then dissolve in cloud droplets, making the resulting precipitation acidic. When this acid rain falls, it can damage forests, kill fish in lakes, corrode buildings and monuments, and even pose health risks to humans by releasing toxic metals from soil.</p>

